Tutorial: RICH-data¶

This is a basic tutorial for the RICH_data python package.

Setup and configuration¶

Import package¶

First, import the RICH_data package

In [1]:
import RICH_data

Get access token for our shared Google Drive¶

The first time you try to access data stored on our shared RICH Google Drive, you will be asked to provide the client credentials file and to sign in with your Google account. This will create a token file with which you will be able to access the RICH Google Drive without needing to sign in again the next time.

For example, let us try to read Dylan's CO2 data:

In [2]:
co2_data = RICH_data.DylanAirCO2Data().data

Plots¶

I put a couple of plots in the RICH_data.plots sub-package. Please let me know if you would like to add some of your own plots, or if you have any requests for new plots!

Example plots¶

Here are a map of Switzerland and a histogram with 14C data from Switzerland:

In [5]:
fig, ax = RICH_data.plots.plot_Switzerland_map()
fig, ax = RICH_data.plots.plot_Switzerland_14C_histogram()

Save plots¶

If you want to save a plot, do this:

In [6]:
fig, ax = RICH_data.plots.plot_Switzerland_map(
    #save = '~/Desktop/plots/map_of_switzerland.png', # uncomment and edit this
    dpi = 300, # dots per inch, dpi = 500 by default
    show = False, # show the plot after saving, True by default
    close = True, # close the plot after saving and showing, True by default
)

Accepted file extensions include png, jpg, pdf, svg, ...

Edit plots: the quick and dirty way¶

If you want to add something to a plot, you can use the returned fig and ax objects. Make sure to select close=False and show=False so that you receive an open fig.

In this example, we add the shape of the Alpine Rhine catchment to the map of Switzerland:

In [7]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import cartopy.crs as ccrs

# Plot map of Switzerland without showing or closing
fig, ax = RICH_data.plots.plot_Switzerland_map(close=False, show=False)

# Read the shape data of NADUF catchments and select Diepoldsau station
catchments = RICH_data.NADUFShapeData().catchments
DI_catchment = catchments.set_index('station').loc['DI']

# Add outline of Alpine Rhine catchment above Diepoldsau to map
crs = ccrs.CRS(catchments.crs) # coordinate reference system
ax.add_geometries(DI_catchment.geometry, crs=crs, zorder=50,
                  facecolor='none', edgecolor='yellow', linewidth=3)

# Add title and show
plt.suptitle('Beautiful map of Switzerland', size=15)
plt.title('(notice the Alpine Rhine catchment in yellow)', size=7)
plt.show()

For any more substantial changes to the plots, you should probably write your own plot functions. Please contact me if you would like to contribute your own plots to the repository!

Stay up to date¶

The RICH_data package is still in development and will be updated regularly with new datasets and bug fixes. To receive these updates from GitHub, run git pull from the RICH-data directory.
